2star  aThis book addresses the prejudices that emerged out of the collision of two pandemics: COVID-19 and racism. Offering a snapshot of experiences through counter story-telling and micro narratives, this collection assesses the racialised responses to the pandemic and investigates acts of discrimination that have occurred within social, political and historical contexts. Capturing the divisive discourses which have dominated this contemporary moment, this is a unique and creative resource that shows how structural racism continues to operate insidiously, offering invaluable insights for policy, practicend critical race and ethnic studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xPolitical aspects. 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xSocial aspects. 0aRacismxPolitical aspects. 0aRacismxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh1 aAnon,, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnyiam, Sharon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHersi, Baar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinchcliffe, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolloman, Tiffany R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIslam, Farjana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKay, Kavyta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKay, Kavyta, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLander, Vini, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMallett, Bruno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoshie-Moses, Ibiyemi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOmar, Yusuf Sheikh, econtributor.4ctb4https:/